<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Taiwan-Earthquake     02-13 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-Earthquake,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Jolts Eastern Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake centered off Taiwan's
eastern coast violently shook houses in the capital before dawn
today. There were no reports of casualties or damage.
   The Central Weather Bureau said the quake measured 6.9 on the
Richter scale and was centered in the ocean about 40 miles
southeast of Taipei. It struck at 3:15 a.m.
   A bureau official said the epicenter was near the Iriomote islet
by the southern tip of Japan's Ryukyu Islands chain. The official
and Taipei police said no reports of damage or casualties had been
received.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a ten-fold
increase in intensity.
   A magnitude of 6 can cause serious damage in a populated area.
An earthquake of magnitude 7 is capable of widespread, heavy damage
in populated areas.
</TEXT>
