<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-88 0700EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Kremlin-Collisions 1stLd-Writethru a0489 02-13 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kremlin-Collisions, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0489,0745</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Fault `Dangerous Manuevers' of U.S. Warships for
Collisions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to recast and clarify. PICKS up 3nd pvs
`On Friday night, ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Soviet Collisions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S. warships violated Soviet territorial
waters, ignored warnings from patrol craft and made ``dangerous
maneuvers'' that led to collisions with Soviet ships in the Black
Sea, a Soviet admiral charged today.
   Rear Adm. Nikolai P. Markov appeared at a hastily called news
briefing to give the first detailed Kremlin version of the incident
that happened off the Crimean peninsula, in which two Soviet navy
vessels grazed the American warships.
   On Friday night, the Defense Ministry accused the American
vessels of violating Soviet waters, but did not mention any
physical contact between them and Soviet ships.
   U.S. Navy officials said the cruiser USS Yorktown and the
destroyer USS Caron were deliberately bumped while exercising their
right to pass through international waters.
   However, Markov and Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I.
Gerasimov told reporters the U.S. warships were knowingly violating
Soviet waters, and said the collisions were the fault of the
American captains.
   Unlike the United States, which claims a three-mile territorial
limit, the Soviet Union claims a 12-mile limit along its coast.
   Gerasimov said U.S. Ambassador Jack Matlock had been summoned to
the Foreign Ministry today, where Deputy Foreign Minister Alexander
Bessmertnykh read him a ``strong protest.
   ``The Soviet side cannot but view the actions of the United
States Navy as aimed at undermining the process of improvement in
Soviet-American relations which has appeared recently,'' Gerasimov
said, quoting from the protest.
   U.S. Navy Cmdr. Richard Schiff, a lawyer, said Friday in
Washington that any country claiming a 12-mile territorial limit
``must allow for innocent passage by the ships of all nations.''
   But Markov and Gerasimov said Soviet law does not provide for
the right of innocent passage in Black Sea waters, which the
Soviets have longed claimed as their own.
   Markov was repeatedly asked to specify what he meant by
``dangerous maneuvers,'' and said the American warships had been
warned both before and after entering Soviet waters.
   ``Generally one can and should regard the very fact of entering
Soviet territorial waters as dangerous maneuvering'' he said.
   He said the two Soviet warships, identified by Pentagon
officials as a Krivak-class frigate and a Mirka-class patrol boat,
were on a ``basically parallel course'' with the U.S. vessels when
the grazings occurred.
   The larger Krivak-class vessel brushed the left side of the
Yorktown, while the Caron was grazed on the same side by the patrol
craft, U.S. officials said.
   Both U.S. and Soviet officials have said the grazings caused no
injuries.
   Markov did not name the Soviet warships, but a small chart
displayed at the briefing identified them as the frigate Bezzavetny
and the patrol ship SKR-6.
   According to the chart, the American warships, steaming
eastward, entered Soviet waters at about 11 a.m. Moscow time south
of Sevastopol, headquarters of the Soviet Black Sea fleet.
   Markov said at one time, the two American ships were as close as
9.2 miles to shore. He said they remained in Soviet territorial
waters following the grazings.
   The Yorktown left Soviet waters at 12:21 p.m. Moscow time south
of the resort city of Yalta, and the Caron, sailing north of the
cruiser, followed about a half-hour later, according to the chart.
   At last notice, the two U.S. vessels were back to ``routine
operations'' in the Black Sea, Navy Capt. Gerry Flynn said Friday
in Washington.
   Markov said the Friday incident was the third of its kind in
recent years.
   In March 1986, the same two ships, the Yorktown and the Caron,
violated Soviet territorial waters in the Black Sea, he said, and
two American warships penetrated Soviet waters off Kamchatka in the
Soviet Far East last year.
   In Washington, a high-ranking State Department official,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said that although the
department had protested the Soviet's behavior, he did not expect
the incident to disturb a U.S.-Soviet effort to narrow differences
on arms control, human rights, regional disputes and bilateral
issues.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz is scheduled to go to Moscow
in two weeks to further those efforts and talk about a U.S.-Soviet
summit meeting tentatively scheduled in the Soviet capital in the
spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
