<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Biden 1stLd-Writethru   02-13 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biden, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0456,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Undergoes Surgery To Correct Aneurysm in Artery to Brain</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Tops with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Biden condition this
morning, picking up 6th pvs, bgng: Smith said</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr. was alert and talking
with family members today after undergoing surgery at Walter Reed
Army Medical Center to correct an aneurysm in an artery supplying
blood to his brain.
   The 45-year-old Deleware Democrat was ``progressing
satisfactorily'' this morning and was ``as comfortable as
possible,'' hospital spokesman Pete Esker said.
   Biden underwent a surgical procedure known as a ``clipping'' to
correct the aneurysm, which is a sac formed by local enlargement of
the weakened wall of an artery.
   Esker said Biden's aneurysm was within his cranium, underneath
the brain but not inside the brain itself.
   Pete Smith, an aide to Biden, said Biden was listed in
``seriously ill'' condition but was expected to suffer no
significant aftereffects from the surgery.
   The surgery ``did not involve the removal of any brain tissue
and there is every indication that the senator will recover
satisfactorily,'' Smith said. ``He is awake, alert, oriented and
moving all extremities well. The length of his hospital stay will
depend on his continued progress.''
   ``Clipping'' is a microsurgical technique in which a minute
metal clip is slipped around the aneurysm, parallel to the artery.
The aneurysm is then deflated and the artery heals. The clip is
left in place.
   Smith said the surgery was performed in Friday afternoon but
there was no immediate information on when it began or how long it
took.
   ``I am told that he is in intensive care, which Walter Reed said
is normal for surgical patients, and his family is with him at the
hospital,'' Smith said. Biden and his wife, Jill, have three
children.
   Biden was admitted to the hospital early Friday after being
transferred from St. Francis Hospital in Wilmington, Del., where
the senator lives.
   Biden, a three-term senator, had been complaining for a couple
of weeks about what had been diagnosed as a pinched nerve in his
neck.
   He wore a neck brace two weeks ago during hearings on the
proposed Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty with the Soviet
Union. He was ill and unable to vote last week on the confirmation
of Anthony Kennedy to the Supreme Court. Biden, as chairman of the
Senate Judiciary Commitee, had led the committee hearings on
Kennedy's nomination to the top court.
   This week, Biden felt well enough to appear for several speaking
engagements at colleges on the East Coast.
   The senator last June announced he was a candidate for the
presidency, but withdrew from the race in September in the wake of
disclosures that he committed plagiarism during law school and
exaggerated his academic accomplishments during campaign stops.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
