<2ND_LINE>AM-Surrogate Mom,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby M's Father, Surrogate Mother To Try Working Out Visitation
Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple locked in a legal tug-of-war
over Baby M will meet with Mary Beth Whitehead-Gould in an attempt
to reach a settlement on visitation for the surrogate mother, a
newspaper reported Saturday.
   William and Elizabeth Stern agreed to a private meeting ``after
much soul-searching,'' said their attorney, Gary N. Skoloff, The
Star-Ledger of Newark reported.
   When the state Supreme Court ruled on the case earlier this
month, it directed a Superior Court judge to set visitation
guidelines for Mrs. Whitehead-Gould and the nearly 2-year-old child.
   The state's highest court overturned a lower court decision that
upheld a $10,000 contract under which Mrs. Whitehead-Gould was
artificially inseminated with Stern's sperm and bore the child for
him and his wife.
   In addition to stripping her of her parental rights, the lower
court last March 31 awarded custody of the baby to the Sterns.
   The Supreme Court maintained custody for the Sterns, but voided
the contract and and the termination of Mrs. Whitehead-Gould's
parental rights, and ruled she was entitled a hearing on visiting
her child. She now gets to visit the child two hours a week, under
a temporary visitation order.
   As of late last week, a court date for a visitation hearing
before Superior Court Judge Birger M. Sween had not been set.
   Harold Cassidy, attorney for Mrs. Whitehead-Gould, did not say
what visitation she would seek during the meeting with the Sterns,
or when the meeting would take place, the newspaper said.
   The proposed meeting marks the first time the Sterns have
pursued an out-of-court settlement in the dispute over Baby M,
named Melissa by the Sterns.
   The Sterns ``have decided, after much soul-searching and
additional professional advice, that it is in the best interest of
Melissa Stern to seek a meeting'' with the surrogate and her
husband, Dean Gould, Skoloff said.
   Cassidy did not return a phone call to his home on Saturday.
There was no answer at Skoloff's office.
</TEXT>
