<FILEID>AP-NR-02-13-88 0011EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Refugees     02-13 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Refugees,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Higher U.S. Refugee Entry Ceilings Urged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anticipating higher numbers of refugees from
Southeast Asia and Soviet bloc countries, two organizations urged
the United States on Friday to raise entry ceilings rather than
shift immigration quotas among regions to compensate.
   The U.S. Committee for Refugees, a refugee protection agency,
and the Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society, migration agency of the U.S.
Jewish Community, urged the Reagan administration and Congress to
invoke emergency procedures of the 1980 U.S. Refugee Act for
raising the total number of admissions.
   The administration has been considering a shift of 5,000 from
the Southeast Asian entry quota to provide for additional places
for Soviet Jews and Armenians from Europe, said USCR Director Roger
P. Winter in a statement.
   Such a shift would have a ``disastrous impact'' on the safety of
Vietnamese ``boat people'' refugees fleeing to Thailand, Winter
said. This is because temporary refugee entry into Thailand depends
on prospects for resettlement elsewhere.
   The government is also proposing to reallocate 4,000 entry
places originally allocated for 1988 refugees from Africa, the Near
East and Latin America, Winter said.
   The increased refugee flow from the Soviet Union and other bloc
countries is ``a direct result of the foreign policy successes of
this administration,'' said Hebrew Immigrant Aid Society official
Karl D. Zukerman in a telegram to Secretary of State George Shultz.
   ``Such a challenge to our human rights and refugee policies
cannot go unanswered, nor should the lives and dignity of one set
of refugees be balanced against others,'' Zukerman said.
</TEXT>
